00:07:16.910 --> 00:07:22.570
And I'm sure most of you will
agree with me that the job

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:28.070
of accessibility in terms of website,
application, design lies in code,

00:07:28.070 --> 00:07:30.460
what that software looks like,
what that code looks like,

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:31.790
how it's written.

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:34.890
And design; what the website looks
like on the front-end, the colors,

00:07:34.890 --> 00:07:37.660
the fonts,
all of those sorts of things.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:41.960
And the misconception is that
that's where that work ends,

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:45.430
and that's completely false, right?

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:49.170
But that is what a lot of
people go through life thinking.

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:54.380
Although, we wouldn't really
be talking about the breadth

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:59.350
of accessibility if we're not talking
about the content on a website.

00:07:59.350 --> 00:08:03.610
If that content that is being
written, whether it is written

00:08:03.610 --> 00:08:06.950
or whether it's visual, if that
content is accessible to everyone

00:08:06.950 --> 00:08:07.950
who's using that site.

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:14.310
If you are somebody who works in
social media, accessibility needs

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:15.920
to be a part of your process.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:19.870
If you are somebody who works
in marketing, who strategizes,

00:08:19.870 --> 00:08:22.290
accessibility needs to
be part of that process.

00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:26.390
Even things like speed and
security have a lot of overlap

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:32.820
in terms of prioritizing, making
sure that their site is accessible.

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:39.350
HR, like,
if you work at all on a website,

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:41.770
accessibility is
your responsibility.

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:47.430
I won't be talking a lot about event
accessibility in this presentation,

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:52.150
even though WordPress event
accessibility is an enormous issue,

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.320
and it's very important,
and it needs a lot of work.

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:59.020
I wanted to keep this focused
specifically to websites, but tons

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:01.310
of this information
is going to overlap.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:04.970
So if you are anyone who works on
a website, if you have a website,

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:07.990
if you manage a website,
if you add content to a website,

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:11.870
if you maintain a website, if you
optimize websites, there’s a lot

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:12.870
in here for you.

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:24.620
I believe that our perception
of accessibility is also limited

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:31.110
in terms of who it is that we are
making a website accessible for.

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:34.280
Especially if you are new to
the realm of accessibility,

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:37.930
your preconceived notions about
who you're solving problems

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:40.550
for might be very limited; and
that might not be your fault,

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:43.630
because the representation
that we do see in terms

00:09:43.630 --> 00:09:48.400
of accessibility tends to include
people with physical disabilities.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:50.860
What you're seeing on
the screen right now

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:53.800
are the first seven image
results when I searched

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:57.530
on a particular stock
website’s accessibility.

00:09:57.530 --> 00:10:00.930
And all of these images
feature people in wheelchairs,

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:04.540
they feature people who are blind, or
who are using assistive technology.

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:11.980
And It's not just people in
wheelchairs or people who are blind

00:10:11.980 --> 00:10:14.080
that need accessible
websites, right?

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:17.350
But that is sort of the story
that's being told in a lot

00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:21.133
of the content that we see online

00:10:21.133 --> 00:10:23.470
when we're learning
about accessibility.

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:27.440
So when we discuss
accessibility solutions

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.340
when we have this preconceived
notion, we've already decided

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:32.780
what the problems are, right?

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:35.440
Before you build anything, no matter
what it is that you're building,

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:37.850
whether it's something virtual
or something physical, you have

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:41.770
to know what the problems are
that you're trying to solve,

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:44.550
and I think all of us
can identify with that.

00:10:44.550 --> 00:10:48.450
Chances are, within your job,
you are a problem solver.

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:51.660
Isn’t that what we do when we
write, develop software?

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:54.170
When we engineer something,
when we market to people,

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:55.970
we're trying to solve a problem.

00:10:55.970 --> 00:10:58.210
We already know how to do this.

00:10:58.210 --> 00:11:01.640
We are already familiar with
the Identify the problem,

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:07.020
and find the methods
to solve the problem.

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:09.732
When it comes to
website accessibility,

00:11:09.733 --> 00:11:10.910
I believe that we just sort

00:11:10.910 --> 00:11:16.080
of have to expand that scope in
order to find the appropriate methods

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:17.930
to solve the right problems
for the right people.

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:23.940
So who does accessibility benefit?

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:28.000
The short answer is
accessibility benefits everybody.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.390
The whole point of this,
Accessibility Beyond Blindness,

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:35.540
is accessibility doesn't just
benefit blind or low vision people

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:37.410
who are accessing your
website, which is kind

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.880
of what that
conception tends to be.

00:11:39.880 --> 00:11:45.570
When I'm speaking about disabilities
in this talk, I'm talking

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:48.730
about both permanent and
temporary disabilities.

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:53.250
And in this case, a disability
is something that makes it harder

00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:56.160
for you to achieve a
goal the way a person

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:58.910
without that disability
would achieve that goal.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:02.790
For example, if I'm on a
website and there's a button

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:06.210
that's supposed to go to another
page, and I click on that button

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:10.390
and it doesn't work,
it just is broken, that is a problem

00:12:10.390 --> 00:12:11.490
that affects everyone.

00:12:11.490 --> 00:12:13.910
It doesn't matter what disability
I may have or not have,

00:12:13.910 --> 00:12:17.210
it doesn't matter my access,
it doesn't matter my education.

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:17.810
It's broken.

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:20.790
That affects everyone
in the same way.

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:26.700
However, if that button has
really unclear anchor text

00:12:28.610 --> 00:12:31.770
that just says, you know,
Click here for more.

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:37.010
Perhaps somebody who is
neurotypical might be able

00:12:37.010 --> 00:12:41.210
to put various pieces of that
page together and figure out

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:43.790
where that button goes,
and feel confident in being able

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:46.330
to click that button to
get to the next step.

00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:48.880
There are people who will
really struggle with that

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:52.480
and not feel confident in
clicking that button to understand

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:53.550
where it goes.

00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:56.630
So now we've created
a rift in terms of

00:12:56.630 --> 00:12:59.740
what some people are struggling
with and what some people aren't.

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:02.030
We've solved one problem and we
haven't solved another problem.

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:09.090
So lots of people benefit
from accessibility, right?

00:13:09.090 --> 00:13:11.170
And this is definitely
not a comprehensive list.

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:18.320
I'm sure there's examples that I am
missing, but these are people that,

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:22.860
in my experience, tend to get
overlooked when we are strategizing

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:23.880
about accessibility.

00:13:25.410 --> 00:13:28.220
Neurodivergent people
benefit from accessibility.

00:13:28.220 --> 00:13:30.460
And when I'm talking about
neurodivergence, if you don't know

00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:34.670
what that term means, being
neurodivergent means having a brain

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:40.410
that works differently from the
average or neurotypical person.

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:42.680
This might be differences
in social preferences.

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:44.040
This might be ways of learning.

00:13:44.040 --> 00:13:45.560
This might be ways
of communicating.

00:13:45.560 --> 00:13:48.820
And it might be ways of
perceiving your environment.

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:52.400
Examples of neurodivergent,
again, not a comprehensive list,

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:56.030
could be people with attention
deficit disorders, ADHD,

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:59.170
people with severe anxiety,
people with epilepsy.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:02.590
Epilepsy is considered
a neurodivergence.

00:14:02.590 --> 00:14:06.270
People who are autistic on the
spectrum, as you might say.

00:14:06.270 --> 00:14:10.000
Anyone with a mental disability,
a cognitive impairment,

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.460
or a mental illness
that is strong enough

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:15.700
that affects that person enough
to affect their use of a website.

00:14:15.700 --> 00:14:18.700
These are all people that we
need to be thinking about.

00:14:18.700 --> 00:14:20.684
Now, you might be
thinking to yourself,

00:14:20.685 --> 00:14:22.320
Well, I'm not an expert in ADHD.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:23.760
I'm not an expert in autism.

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:29.990
How am I supposed to anticipate
those needs? It doesn't take a lot

00:14:29.990 --> 00:14:37.990
to do some research into how
experiences can be challenging online

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.820
for people with neurodivergence,
and a lot of it comes down

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:44.330
to clarity and choice.

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:51.600
So content that is hard or
impossible to ingest, user journeys

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:55.545
that are stressful,
flashing or automatic movement

00:14:55.546 --> 00:14:58.233
that can't be paused
or interacted with,

00:15:00.267 --> 00:15:02.950
all of these things
can affect people

00:15:02.950 --> 00:15:06.120
with neurodivergence, and make
using a website very difficult.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:09.660
And there is a challenge in
that, which is that

00:15:09.660 --> 00:15:16.870
if you are a neurotypical person,
you have, I have an unconscious bias.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:17.840
I will make assumptions,

00:15:17.841 --> 00:15:19.860
you will make assumptions
as I create a website,

00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:22.830
as you create a website
that you will be understood,

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:27.810
that you will make decisions
about communicating information

00:15:27.810 --> 00:15:29.460
in ways that you understand.

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:34.610
And there are many people out
there who don't follow that

00:15:34.610 --> 00:15:36.370
same thought process.

00:15:36.370 --> 00:15:39.450
So taking the time to understand
that, and taking the time

00:15:39.450 --> 00:15:45.970
to make sure that information
is as clear and concise

00:15:45.970 --> 00:15:48.970
as possible is incredibly
important, and we'll go over,

00:15:48.970 --> 00:15:50.430
a little bit later, some ways

00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:51.430
in which we can do that.

00:15:53.560 --> 00:15:57.390
Accessibility also benefits
people with learning disabilities.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:02.480
A very common example of that
is dyslexia, which makes it hard

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:04.450
for you to read.

00:16:04.450 --> 00:16:07.350
People with dyslexia often
find that words move around,

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:09.990
or letters move around,
or words might appear backwards,

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:11.110
and so on and so forth.

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:16.530
And a lot of fonts can make
dyslexia worse, can make it harder

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.160
for someone with dyslexia
to read something.

00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:23.470
So If you are publishing
content on the internet,

00:16:23.470 --> 00:16:29.710
it doesn't take a lot to research
what fonts are stronger choices

00:16:29.710 --> 00:16:30.860
for people with dyslexia.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:34.350
When we're talking about
learning disabilities,

00:16:34.350 --> 00:16:36.890
we might also be talking
about simply people

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:40.620
for whom English is not
their first language.

00:16:42.310 --> 00:16:46.440
And that's not to say that
person can't understand English,

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:51.370
but there might be language on
your website that is so localized

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:57.420
to English, to America, or parts of
Europe that maybe somebody coming

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:00.740
from Japan or somebody coming
from Portugal is not going

00:17:00.740 --> 00:17:04.310
to understand, and we'll go
over some of those idioms later.

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:11.270
So just keeping in mind that we
want to create the shortest point

00:17:11.270 --> 00:17:13.690
of contact between
what somebody has to do

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:17.770
and how they can reach their goal.

00:17:17.770 --> 00:17:22.490
And so providing as few steps
as possible on our websites,

00:17:22.490 --> 00:17:28.400
and that includes making it so
that they can read the information

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:31.100
and understand it clearly.

00:17:31.100 --> 00:17:32.790
All of that is
incredibly important.

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:39.300
So these are sort of what I
consider internal factors.

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:41.720
These are things about a
person, about their

00:17:41.720 --> 00:17:46.030
being that might make it challenging
for them to access your website.

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:47.850
Some external factors.

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:49.437
People with poor
internet connections;

00:17:49.438 --> 00:17:50.820
and that doesn't just mean people

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:53.560
that are in impoverished
areas who don't have access

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:55.430
to high-speed internet.

00:17:55.430 --> 00:18:02.080
That could mean that your user
is at a university library,

00:18:02.080 --> 00:18:06.080
and it's finals week,
and everyone is hogging the Wi-Fi.

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:07.790
It could mean that
they're at a coffee shop,

00:18:07.790 --> 00:18:11.490
and that coffee shop just has
cheap Wi-Fi and isn't able

00:18:11.490 --> 00:18:18.040
to load your website as quickly
as you a website builder

00:18:18.040 --> 00:18:23.300
or business owner who pays extra for
high-speed Wi-Fi might experience.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:28.440
And once sites are slow to load,
they tend to load minimal content.

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:30.890
And so this is where site
speed comes into effect

00:18:30.890 --> 00:18:33.530
when we're talking about
accessibility; a good example of that

00:18:33.530 --> 00:18:35.460
being alternative text.

00:18:35.460 --> 00:18:39.310
If your user has a poor
internet connection, the images

00:18:39.310 --> 00:18:41.990
on your site may not load,
or may not load as quickly.

00:18:41.990 --> 00:18:46.820
And if you have strong alternative
text on that page, they don't need

00:18:46.820 --> 00:18:49.910
to worry about the information
they might be missing

00:18:49.910 --> 00:18:51.120
when they can't see that image.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:55.467
We're also talking about
mobile-device users;

00:18:55.468 --> 00:18:56.680
and that's not necessarily

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:01.340
just to say when you talk
about responsivity, we need

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:05.820
to talk about people who
are using older devices.

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:10.050
My dad just got rid of his
flip phone about a year

00:19:10.050 --> 00:19:12.910
and a half ago, and that man was
trying to access the internet

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:13.970
on his flip phone.

00:19:13.970 --> 00:19:16.570
So please think about
my dad [laughs].

00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:20.820
Please think about people
who are using older devices;

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:23.510
devices that are not
iPhones or Android phones.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:27.670
Sometimes people just don't
have access to those devices,

00:19:27.670 --> 00:19:29.970
and so we need to keep those people
in mind when we're looking at,

00:19:31.850 --> 00:19:34.570
How simple can we make it
to access this website?

00:19:36.240 --> 00:19:39.090
We're looking at people
who have limited mobility.

00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:44.510
And that could be a permanent
limitation, a missing arm,

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:46.120
a missing hand, a missing fingers.

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:49.640
That makes it really hard to
use a keyboard or use a mouse

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:51.460
to interact with your site.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:54.090
They may have arthritis
and not really be able

00:19:54.090 --> 00:20:00.580
to scroll through a website as much
as we think they should be able to.

00:20:00.580 --> 00:20:07.100
I'm trying to get you thinking
about the wide variety of people

00:20:07.100 --> 00:20:11.630
and circumstances outside of
what we normally consider.

00:20:11.630 --> 00:20:16.880
When we know the problem,
we can anticipate a solution, right?

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:20.040
Even when I think about limited
mobility... Have you ever tried

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:26.080
to navigate a website while holding
a screaming, crying, wiggling baby?

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:30.610
There are so many times in
your life where your ability

00:20:30.610 --> 00:20:34.950
to navigate something is
challenged or taken away from you,

00:20:34.950 --> 00:20:38.240
and that can be temporary
or that can be permanent.

00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:39.240
I'm going to take a sip of water.

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:47.150
So this last bullet point...
Just hear me out.

00:20:47.150 --> 00:20:52.080
Recently, I was in a grocery store,
and I already had a cart full

00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:54.210
of heavy things,
and it was the end of the day

00:20:54.210 --> 00:20:56.080
and I was tired,
and I didn't want to be there,

00:20:56.080 --> 00:20:59.240
and I don't like going to the grocery
store, but I was there anyway.

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:04.790
And I was on my phone,
looking at a website for a recipe

00:21:04.790 --> 00:21:06.286
that I wanted to
make, and I was trying

00:21:06.287 --> 00:21:07.520
to find the list of ingredients.

00:21:08.710 --> 00:21:13.500
If you've ever tried to access
a recipe, like go on Pinterest

00:21:13.500 --> 00:21:16.620
and find a recipe, and click through
and go to that person's blog,

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:19.890
you know the challenges that
tend to come with those pages.

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:25.560
I was forced to scroll all
the way down to the bottom

00:21:25.560 --> 00:21:30.010
of this enormous blog post in order
to actually find the recipe itself,

00:21:30.010 --> 00:21:33.140
because this person wanted to tell
me a story about their grandmother,

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:35.700
or, I don't know,
something completely irrelevant

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.100
to what I needed.

00:21:37.100 --> 00:21:43.390
So I'm trying to scroll and
the page is packed with ads:

00:21:43.390 --> 00:21:47.160
banner ads, inline ads, pop-up ads.

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:51.680
And so every time I try to scroll,
I'm accidentally tapping on ads.

00:21:51.680 --> 00:21:55.920
And the second an ad opens,
I have to try to find the little X

00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:59.060
to close out of that ad, and
usually they make them incredibly,

00:21:59.060 --> 00:21:59.920
incredibly tiny.

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:03.380
And so I'm trying to angle my
hand to get the right pressure

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:07.020
to get the tiny X; and usually I
don't, so I end up actually tapping

00:22:07.020 --> 00:22:07.890
on the ad itself.

00:22:07.890 --> 00:22:10.680
And now I need to go all the
way to the top-left corner

00:22:10.680 --> 00:22:12.160
of my phone to try to go back.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:16.560
So I'm stressed out [chuckles], OK?

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:21.240
There are so many ads and they
won't stop, and I'm scrolling

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:22.190
and scrolling.

00:22:22.190 --> 00:22:25.890
I finally get to a video, and I
think, Great, they made a video

00:22:25.890 --> 00:22:26.600
about this recipe.

00:22:26.600 --> 00:22:29.890
I'll just open up the video.
There are no captions on the video.

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:33.400
I'm sorry, I'm not the kind of
person that will play the audio

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:34.780
of a video in the
middle of a Target.

00:22:34.780 --> 00:22:37.750
I can't do that.

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:41.920
The video would have been great
to just see what she was using

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:44.010
and go ahead and grab it,
but there were no captions

00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:45.090
to this video so I had to go back.

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:52.610
I finally get to the recipe,
but the Wi-Fi connection

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:59.340
in this Target is middling,
and so the ads are still populating.

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:02.650
The ads from higher up on
the page are still loading.

00:23:02.650 --> 00:23:05.430
So I get to the recipe list,
and then it shoots down

00:23:05.430 --> 00:23:08.630
because an ad has populated and
forced the content down the page.

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:13.910
I didn't make the dang recipe.

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:14.520
[laughs]

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:15.800
I never made it.

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:21.510
I gave up, because it was so
impossible for me, an able-bodied,

00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:26.723
a neurotypical person,
with no necessarily challenges

00:23:26.724 --> 00:23:31.470
to my mobility, no learning
disabilities, no disability

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:33.250
to use this website.

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:39.820
These are the kinds of things that
we have to keep in mind, right?

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:42.510
That yes,
we are designing websites.

00:23:42.510 --> 00:23:43.590
We are building websites.

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:45.110
We are creating solutions.

00:23:46.970 --> 00:23:50.050
And we are keeping people
with disabilities in mind,

00:23:50.050 --> 00:23:52.360
but that's not where the work ends.

00:23:52.360 --> 00:23:56.550
There are so many things that this
particular website could have done

00:23:56.550 --> 00:23:58.270
to improve my experience.

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.710
Lots of recipe sites
will now have a jump

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:03.330
to recipe button at the very
top, which you just tap,

00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:06.310
and it brings you all the
way down to the recipe.

00:24:06.310 --> 00:24:07.840
That's great.

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:09.910
I don't really understand why
you can't just put the recipe

00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:12.770
at the top of the
page above the fold.

00:24:12.770 --> 00:24:15.480
Why do I have an extra
step in my user journey?

00:24:15.480 --> 00:24:20.780
And then when I do click that button,
those ads are still populating.

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:24.230
So I get to the recipe,
and then I'm forced away from it.

00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:27.880
It's incredibly stressful.

00:24:28.910 --> 00:24:31.950
And these are the things that
we have to be thinking about.

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:37.970
About that person at 6:30 at Target
who's just trying to figure out

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:40.050
if they need [Inaudible 00:24:39]

00:24:40.050 --> 00:24:41.050
or not.

00:24:43.950 --> 00:24:45.840
So we’ve talked a lot about people.

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:49.670
The people beyond blind folks and
people in wheelchairs that we want

00:24:49.670 --> 00:24:52.720
to think about when we are
optimizing for accessibility.

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:56.810
If you want to take all the
altruism out of it and get

00:24:56.810 --> 00:25:01.210
to the business side of things,
like, How does focusing more

00:25:01.210 --> 00:25:06.100
on accessibility help my website,
help my traffic, help my sales,

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:11.850
help my business?
SEO and accessibility, in my mind,

00:25:11.850 --> 00:25:13.360
are in love with each other.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:14.420
They're a couple.

00:25:14.420 --> 00:25:15.210
They adore each other.

00:25:15.210 --> 00:25:18.660
There is so much overlap when
it comes to accessibility

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:22.030
and SEO best practices,
because the goal is the same.

00:25:22.030 --> 00:25:26.030
The goal is to make sure that as
many people as humanly possible

00:25:26.030 --> 00:25:28.360
can easily use your website.

00:25:29.910 --> 00:25:33.420
Accessibility helps search-engine
algorithms understand

00:25:33.420 --> 00:25:36.400
your content better, and it
helps to improve searchability.

00:25:37.670 --> 00:25:40.979
Accessible websites are
just easier-to-use sites,

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:46.360
and Google wants, loves to rank
sites that are easy to use, and sites

00:25:46.360 --> 00:25:51.760
that communicate that your site is
the best answer to someone's problem.

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:55.180
You could have the best
product in the whole world

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:59.050
to sell someone,
but if that site is inaccessible

00:25:59.050 --> 00:26:02.280
and doesn't communicate that
information to everyone,

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:03.480
how is Google
supposed to know that?

00:26:05.820 --> 00:26:09.460
The more accessible your
site, the more it checks all

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:11.250
of Google's boxes, right?

00:26:11.250 --> 00:26:14.760
If the site is easy to read and
uses headings and subheadings

00:26:14.760 --> 00:26:17.710
and bullet points,
if the images have clear

00:26:17.710 --> 00:26:22.150
and fantastic alternative text,
if the navigation is awesome

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:25.890
and easy to use, if it's mobile
responsive, if it loads quickly,

00:26:25.890 --> 00:26:28.580
if it has high traffic
and low bounces,

00:26:28.580 --> 00:26:31.180
because people aren't abandoning
your site in the middle of a Target.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:36.850
All of these things are going
to help Google help you.

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:39.710
So even if we want to take the
people out of it and just go after,

00:26:39.710 --> 00:26:42.650
Well, what do the robots think?
The robots want your site

00:26:42.650 --> 00:26:44.620
to be accessible, OK?

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:49.540
This goes the same for other engines
and algorithms, not just Google.

00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:53.990
Videos with captions, as I just
complained about, are so much better.

00:26:53.990 --> 00:26:59.740
They perform better on social
media than ones without, right?

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:02.770
That's kind of a definitive
thing of TikTok videos now,

00:27:02.770 --> 00:27:04.970
which is they have that
text that is, like,

00:27:04.970 --> 00:27:07.110
populating as the
person is speaking.

00:27:07.110 --> 00:27:08.130
Why?

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:09.980
Because people like them.

00:27:09.980 --> 00:27:11.560
They watch them.

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:12.430
They share them.

00:27:12.430 --> 00:27:14.370
They find them valuable.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:18.480
And so the algorithms will see
this, and then add value

00:27:18.480 --> 00:27:20.710
to that video and say, OK,
I'm going to push this video

00:27:20.710 --> 00:27:24.020
to more people because it's
accessible to them and they're going

00:27:24.020 --> 00:27:28.670
to be able to enjoy it.
Hear me out.

00:27:28.670 --> 00:27:32.060
I know this image is a complete
non-sequitur, [chuckles]

00:27:32.060 --> 00:27:33.250
but I have a point, OK?

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:37.570
And I'm stealing this point
from my friend Michelle

00:27:37.570 --> 00:27:39.450
because she's talked about
it on her podcast before,

00:27:39.450 --> 00:27:40.930
and I think it's
extremely pertinent.

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:46.070
In the ‘90s, there was a
fantastic show called Queer Eye

00:27:46.070 --> 00:27:50.870
for the Straight Guy.
It was a reality show about a group

00:27:50.870 --> 00:27:53.970
of gay men who would find a
straight guy and give him a whole,

00:27:53.970 --> 00:27:58.120
like, life makeover, like new clothes
and all of this kind of stuff.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:28:00.030
It was very wholesome,
and it was very sweet,

00:28:00.030 --> 00:28:05.740
and it was very groundbreaking
in terms of asking for tolerance

00:28:05.740 --> 00:28:07.110
for the gay community, right?

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:13.070
Like showing gay people on TV,
helping other people, right?

00:28:13.070 --> 00:28:16.620
And the whole goal was
tolerance in a time

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:19.760
when the queer community
was not tolerated.

00:28:21.400 --> 00:28:22.700
The show has recently got a reboot.

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:23.860
It's fantastic.

00:28:23.860 --> 00:28:26.460
It's called Queer Eye.
That's the five people you're looking

00:28:26.460 --> 00:28:27.740
at right now.

00:28:27.740 --> 00:28:28.620
They're the hosts.

00:28:28.620 --> 00:28:29.620
I love this show.

00:28:31.570 --> 00:28:36.240
And their goal is acceptance;
not tolerance, but accepted.

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:39.860
Because would you rather
be tolerated in a space,

00:28:39.860 --> 00:28:42.480
or would you rather be accepted?

00:28:42.480 --> 00:28:47.000
Would you rather feel that people
just aren't complaining about you,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.350
or would you rather feel
that people want you there?

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:55.960
So much of accessibility is
about inclusion; and inclusion is

00:28:55.960 --> 00:28:59.290
about making people feel like
you want them to be there.

00:28:59.290 --> 00:29:04.660
Why would you not want people to feel
like they belong on your website?

00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:08.600
Why would you not want people to
feel like going to your website,

00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:10.010
it's like it was made for them?

00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:13.470
You want them to be reading
your content, you want them

00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:15.980
to be buying your products,
or signing up for your services.

00:29:15.980 --> 00:29:17.770
That's what all this is
about, right?

00:29:17.770 --> 00:29:23.650
We design websites because
we want people to use them

00:29:23.650 --> 00:29:25.360
and do things with them.

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:28.560
I stole this quote from UNC
Greensboro, I'll say that.

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:32.505
Web accessibility works to
inclusively enable access

00:29:32.506 --> 00:29:38.767
to a website by all users, regardless
of the user's level of ability,

00:29:38.767 --> 00:29:40.930
condition,
or circumstances.

