00:49:02.460 --> 00:49:06.330
There's a question from Susan:
Is scrolling content the same

00:49:06.330 --> 00:49:07.450
as a long page?

00:49:07.450 --> 00:49:09.070
How would you break it up?

00:49:09.070 --> 00:49:10.380
I try and add headings.

00:49:10.380 --> 00:49:15.100
And if more than three or four,
I add a table of contents.

00:49:15.100 --> 00:49:16.795
Are those valid solutions?

00:49:18.200 --> 00:49:19.860
 ALLIE: A table of
contents is always going

00:49:19.860 --> 00:49:21.040
to be a valid solution.

00:49:22.990 --> 00:49:25.610
So when you're saying long
page, from what I understand,

00:49:25.610 --> 00:49:30.340
that’s like one of those
pages that's a lot of content,

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:34.950
and you might be able to, like, use
an ID to jump to different sections.

00:49:34.950 --> 00:49:36.390
I think that's what
you're talking about.

00:49:36.390 --> 00:49:38.650
 AMANDA: I’m thinking
of, like, a recipe page,

00:49:38.650 --> 00:49:40.040
like you were talking
about earlier.

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:41.040
 ALLIE: Yes.

00:49:42.090 --> 00:49:44.590
Always, always,
always table of contents.

00:49:44.590 --> 00:49:45.860
I love blog posts.

00:49:45.860 --> 00:49:48.070
I think Kinsta,
their blog does that really well.

00:49:48.070 --> 00:49:50.790
Like, they always have a table
of contents at the beginning

00:49:50.790 --> 00:49:52.860
that go to all of
their subheadings.

00:49:52.860 --> 00:49:55.940
I just think everyone should
do that no matter what,

00:49:55.940 --> 00:49:58.150
if you have subheadings on
that page and it makes sense.

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:04.610
So yes, to answer your question,
those are very valid solutions.

00:50:04.610 --> 00:50:05.030
Yes.

